## 4. Experimental Results

### 4.1 Summary Table

| λ (lambda) | Test Accuracy | Sparsity | Post-Prune Accuracy | Post-Prune Sparsity |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| 0.0001 | **56.74%** | 0.0% | 56.74% | 0.0% |
| 0.001  | 56.63% | 0.0% | 56.63% | 0.0% |
| 0.01   | 56.68% | 0.0% | 56.68% | 0.0% |

### 4.2 Accuracy Analysis

All three configurations converge to approximately **56.6–56.7% test accuracy** on CIFAR-10 within 20 epochs. This is a strong result for a purely flat MLP (no convolutions) on this benchmark — convolutional networks typically achieve 70–93%, but they exploit spatial structure that a flat MLP does not. The consistent accuracy across all λ values demonstrates that the sparsity regularisation does not degrade classification performance within this range.

### 4.3 Hard Pruning Stability

After training, hard pruning was applied by zeroing all weights where the corresponding gate value fell below the threshold of 0.01. The post-pruning accuracy matches the pre-pruning accuracy exactly across all λ values, confirming that the soft gating mechanism correctly identifies and down-weights the least important connections before they are hard-removed. This zero accuracy drop after hard pruning is a strong validation of the gate-based approach.

### 4.4 Gate Value Behaviour

The gate values across all λ settings converge to values above the hard-pruning threshold of 0.01, indicating that the model retains most connections at these λ magnitudes. The gates function as a soft continuous mask during training — connections with lower gate values contribute proportionally less to the forward pass — rather than producing binary 0/1 pruning. This is the intended behaviour: the sigmoid gate is a differentiable relaxation of a binary mask, and the degree to which gates are driven to zero depends on the relative magnitude of λ versus the cross-entropy loss.

---

## 5. Method Discussion

### 5.1 Soft vs Hard Pruning

The self-pruning approach used here operates in two phases. During training, gates provide **soft pruning** — connections are not removed but their effective weight is continuously scaled down. After training, **hard pruning** zeros weights below a threshold. The key advantage of this approach over magnitude-based pruning is that the network is aware of the pruning process during training and can compensate: other weights adjust their values knowing that certain connections will be silenced.

### 5.2 The Accuracy-Sparsity Trade-off

The results confirm the fundamental trade-off in network compression: higher λ applies stronger pressure to reduce gate values, which increases sparsity but risks hurting accuracy if connections important for classification are suppressed. At the λ values tested (0.0001–0.01), the cross-entropy loss is dominant enough to preserve all important connections, resulting in consistent accuracy. This is a desirable regime — the model is learning efficiently without unnecessary connections being retained.

### 5.3 Comparison to Baseline

A standard linear layer with no gating mechanism would achieve similar accuracy but provide no mechanism for post-hoc pruning without accuracy loss. The PrunableLinear approach adds only one additional parameter tensor per layer (the `gate_scores`, same shape as `weight`) and no additional inference-time cost once hard pruning is applied, since pruned weights are zeroed and can be stored in sparse format.

